desc: NOS (new old stock) Western Electric 10A payphone.  This vintage 1980 telephone was made to replace a coin phone.  It didn't take coins but was used to make S.O.S. calls, credit card and collect calls.  The phone didn't come with an instruction card, the one I installed came from an out of service same type phone.  The tool shown is used to remove the security screw in order to open the phone.
name: 10A Charge NOS

desc:
When Automatic Electric bought Gray they continued many of Gray's models. This is the first example of a 150GJ I have ever seen made by Automatic Electric. It is a 5 cent model. Gray converted older 2 piece phones such as a 150G to 150GJ, the suffix J signified a handset model. This antique telephone is NOS in it's original box. It looks to be new rather than a rebuild.

I don't know what the suffix "C" stands for, if you do please let me know!
name: AE 150GJC

desc: Automatic Electric 1A Monophone.  This antique telephone was manufactured in Jade Green Bakelite.  The cradle, dial blank and the rings on the handset caps are chrome plated.  The handset cord is a nos Automatic Electric  Extensicord which consists of 4 cloth covered leads braided together with a strip of elastic running between them.
name: AE 1A Jade Green

desc:
Automatic Electric #29 5 cent coin collector.
This would connect electrically to a telephone.  The combination would create a seim-post-pay payphone.  The user would call the desired party without depositing a coin.  Once the party answers a coin would be dropped to allow the conversation.
name: AE 29

desc: Automatic Electric 34, this antique telephone is equipped with the early spit cup handset.  Unlike the later type 40 that has 2 plungers this model has only one in the center of the case between the cradles.
name: AE 34

desc: Automatic Electric 40.  This antique telephone is made of "Peking Red" colored Catalin.  It is equipped with chrome handset bands, and a chrome "cut away" dial finger wheel.  It is also equipped with a chrome fold down carry handle.  The handset cord is a NOS Automatic Electric "Extensicord".
name: AE 40 Red

desc: Automatic Electric 47.  This antique telephone is a multi-line version of the AE 40.  It is equipped with chrome handset bands and a chrome plated dial ringer wheel.
name: AE 47 $250

desc: Automatic Electric 50 nicknamed "the jukebox phone".  The handset and body are Bakelite.  Nice optional chrome dial finger wheel and handset bands.
name: AE 50

desc: Automatic Electric 62. Early AE prepay payphone with AE 40 type handset.  This antique telephone has a nice daisy dial face, numbers only with metal shroud.  It is mounted to a 139A bracket. Beautiful 5 cent antique payphone in original condition.  This is one of the first models Automatic Electric made after purchasing Gray.
name: AE 62

desc: Automatic Electric 62-55 payphone. This antique telephone has a type 40 handset equipped with chrome bands.  The dial shroud is Bakelite and has a nice porcelain "daisy" face, the dial finger wheel is chrome plated.  This is an early prepay 10 cent model.
name: AE 62-55

desc: Automatic Electric 62-55 payphone. This antique telephone has a type 40 handset. The dial shroud is Bakelite and has a nice porcelain "daisy" face. This is an early prepay 10 cent model in terrific original condition.
name: AE 62-55 2

desc: Automatic Electric 64C.  This antique telephone is equipped with an AE 40 type handset and a Bakelite dial shroud with porcelain "daisy" face.  Note the "salad fork" handset hook.  This is a nice original 5 cent prepay payphone.
name: AE 64 C

desc: Automatic Electric 66 E 10.  This antique telephone is equipped with a Bakelite AE 34 type handset and a Bakelite dial shroud with a nice "daisy" face.  This is a prepay 10 cent (dime only) payphone.  It is mounted to a 139A bracket.  Note the nice coin relay cover.  This is another of the early Automatic Electric models.
name: AE 66 E 10

desc: Automatic Electric 66E.  This antique telephone is equipped with a Bakelite AE 34 handset and Bakelite dial shroud with a porcelain "daisy" face.  The 66E is a 5 cent prepay payphone, looks like it was converted or upgraded to work with a dime.  Conversions are very common with payphones.  When a call changed from 5 cents to 10 cents the change was actually made internal to the phone.
name: AE 66E

desc: Automatic Electric 66 E 10. This antique telephone is equipped with an AE 40 type Bakelite handset with chrome bands and a Bakelite dial shroud with a nice "daisy" face.  Take a look at the chrome plated "cut away" dial finger wheel. This is a prepay 10 cent (dime only) payphone.  Note the nice coin relay cover. This is another of the early Automatic Electric models.
name: AE 66E 10 2

desc: Automatic Electric 66E. This antique telephone is equipped with a Bakelite AE 40 handset and Bakelite dial shroud with a porcelain "daisy" face. The 66E is a 5 cent prepay payphone, looks like it was converted or upgraded to work with a dime. Conversions are very common with payphones. When a call changed from 5 cents to 10 cents the change was actually made internal to the phone.
name: AE 66E 3

desc: Automatic Electric 96 E 10.  This antique telephone is one that was used by an independent telephone company.  It is  equipped it with a Stromberg Carlson handset and dial.  The dial shroud is Bakelite.  This is a 10 cent semi-post-pay payphone.
name: AE 96 E10

desc: Automatic Electric 98N non-dial manual payphone.  With this antique telephone all aspects of an outgoing telephone call would have been handled by the operator.  She would have connected the call and asked for payment.  She would have listened as coins were dropped.  It is equipped with an unusual AE 40 type Bakelite handset that has a spit cup.  The coin gauge guard is over the slots to insures that the user reads the instructions before depositing a coin.
name: AE 98 N

desc: Automatic Electric 1A Monophone.  This antique telephone is nicknamed the "High Boy".  It is equipped with an early spit cup handset with nice chrome rings on the caps and an Automatic Electric 24 dial with chrome finger wheel.  The handset cord is an Automatic Electric "Extensicord".
name: AE A1 Monophone

desc: Automatic Electric candlestick telephone with Bakelite base.  This antique telephone is brass and the dial base is Bakelite, most similar phones would be made completely of brass.  Note the nice celluloid number card .
name: AE Bakelite Bottom Low Boy Candlestick Phone

desc: Automatic Electric candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone is made of brass.  Note the tall perch, aka "Highboy".  The dial is an early type 24.
name: AE Brass Bottom High Boy Candlestick Telephone

desc: Automatic Electric candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone is made of brass.  Note the shorted perch on this phone.
name: AE Brass Bottom Low Boy Candlestick Telephone

desc: Automatic Electric Conversion.  There were kits available that would be used to convert non-dial Western Electric candlestick telephones to dial using Automatic Electric parts.  The shaft, base and base cover would be replaced. The original perch, transmitter assembly, hook, receiver and internal components would be re-used.
name: AE Conversion Candlestick Telephone

desc: Automatic Electric Monophone.  This antique telephone has an added Bakelite base section that  houses the bell.  Other similar models without the extra base do not have an internal bell ringer.
name: AE Extended Base

desc: Automatic Electric Monophone, This antique telephone has an additional base section with line keys for multiple telephone line use.  The phone is equipped with an early spit cup handset with nice chrome bands on the caps as well as a NOS Automatic Electric Extensicord.  This telephone is still connected to it's original metal junction box at which point it connects to the house wiring.
name: AE Key Phone

desc: Automatic Electric LPA-82-55.  An automatic, prepay 10 cent payphone.  The body is painted red the plastic parts are red as well, the dial finger wheel is chrome.  Automatic Electric made payphones at this time in 12 colors.
name: AE LPA-82-55 Red

desc: RARE!  Automatic Electric LPB-82-55.  An automatic, prepay 10 cent payphone.  The body is chrome, the plastic parts are yellow, the dial finger wheel is chrome.  The phone has a special coin chute made by the National Rejector Co, the payphone has a coin return button.  This phone came from Edmonton Canada.  The upper housing lock is a Northern Electric MD 9130 (only seen on this model) and the vault lock is a 10L.  It is mounted to a 139A bracket.
name: AE LPB-82-55 Chrome, Special Chute

desc: Automatic Electric LPB-82-55.  An automatic, prepay 10 cent payphone.  The body is painted gray the plastic parts are gray as well.  The dial finger wheel is clear.  Automatic Electric made payphones at this time in 12 colors, the gray is the rarest of all.
name: AE LPB-82-55 Gray

desc: Automatic Electric LPB-82-55.  An automatic, prepay 10 cent payphone.  The body is painted green the plastic parts are green as well, the dial finger wheel is chrome.  Automatic Electric made payphones at this time in 12 colors.
name: AE LPB-82-55 Green

desc: Automatic Electric LPB-82-55.  An automatic, prepay 10 cent payphone.  The body is painted turquoise the plastic parts are turquoise as well, the dial finger wheel is chrome.  Automatic Electric made payphones at this time in 12 colors.
name: AE LPB-82-55 Turquoise

desc: Automatic Electric manual or non-dial candlestick telephone made for the Edwards company.  The Edwards Company likely uses it as part of an intercom system.  There is a signal button on the base.  Note the diretcory attachment on the shaft.
name: AE Manual Candlestick Telephone

desc: Automatic Electric "Space Maker"  desk or wall phone.  These compact phones had all kinds of uses.  They have an induction coil but no bell.  The handset is Bakelite, the phone body is metal.  It is finished in black paint and has nice chrome handset bands and dial finger wheel.
name: AE Spacemaker Black & Chrome

desc: Automatic Electric "Space Maker"  desk or wall phone.  These compact phones had all kinds of uses.  They have an induction coil but no bell.  The handset is plastic, the phone body is metal.  It is finished in blue paint and has a nice chrome dial finger wheel.
name: AE Spacemaker Blue

desc: Automatic Electric "Space Maker" desk or wall phone. These compact phones had all kinds of uses. They have an induction coil but no bell. The handset is plastic, the phone body is metal. It is finished in ivory paint and has a nice chrome dial finger wheel.
name: AE Spacemaker Ivory

desc: Automatic Electric "Space Maker" desk or wall phone. These compact phones had all kinds of uses. They have an induction coil but no bell. The handset is plastic, the phone body is metal. It is finished in red paint and has a nice chrome dial finger wheel.
name: AE Spacemaker Red

desc: Automatic Electric "Stair Step" base candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone is the early model of stair step base type.  It has a smaller transmitter than the later ones, the dial is a type 23 "Mercedes" type.  The physical switch hook linkage is lighter weight and more prone to breaking than the later model.  Note the A in the switch hook.
name: AE Stairstep Base (A) Candlestick Telephone

desc: Automatic Electric "Stair Step" candlestick telephone.  This is the second model with the early type base.  It is equipped with the smaller type 23 or "Mercedes" dial.  Note the Courtesy Pays coin box attachment on the shaft.
name: AE Stairstep Base Candlestick Telephone

desc: Automatic Electric "Strowger", "Potbelly" candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone has what is called the 11 digit dial.  Almon Strowger, a funeral director was losing business to another funeral home with relations to the operator. He invented the automatic dial telephone to combat that problem. Obviously what he invented became huge and was used all over the world and still is in use today. This antique telephone is a beautiful example.
name: AE Strowger Potbelly Candlestick Telephone

desc: I removed this AT&T COCOT (Customer Owned Coin Operated Telephone) from an old pharmacy in Queens NY.  It had been unused for many years.  It was found in very good condition.  The coin scanner is Mars, and the chassis is Protel.  Note the "MADE BY, Western Electric" coin return assembly (ASD).  In my opinion this was originally a Tel. Co. 1D that was taken out of service and reworked to be put into private payphone use.  The upper and lower locks are Abloy.
name: AT&T COCOT Queens NY loc Hall

desc: American Electric "Monophone" cradle telephone.  This antique telephone is the predecessor to the similar models made by Automatic Electric.  It is a non-dial version.  Automatic Electric bought out American Electric and continued with some of their models.
name: American Electric

desc: American Electric manual candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone has a dial blank.  If put into a situation where automatic service is changed over a dial could be added to the telephone.
name: American Electric Dial Blank Candlestick $325

desc: American Electric automatic candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone has an Automatic Electric type 23 or "Mercedes" dial.  .
name: American Electric Dial Candlestick $400

desc: American Electric automatic candlestick telephone made for the Keystone Telephone Co. of Pennsylvania.  Note the Keystone shaped cutout in the switch hook as well as in the telephone card holder.  Also note the very nice porcelain dial center divided up into the individual telephone exchanges that could be called.  The dial is an Automatic Electric type 23.
name: American Electric Keystone Dial Candlestick

desc: American Electric candlestick telephone made for the Keystone Telephone Co. of Pennsylvania.  Note the keystone shaped cutout in the switch hook.
name: American Electric Keystone Nondial $250

desc: American Electric manual candlestick telephone.  Similar to #2 but completely different.  Very heavy and well made example. The base is cast iron painted black and everything above is nickel plated brass.  Nice marked, beveled transmitter.
name: American Electric Nickel 1 Candlestick Telephone

desc: American Electric manual candlestick telephone.  Similar to #1 but completely different.  Very heavy and well made example. The base is cast iron painted black and everything above is nickel plated brass.  Nice marked, beveled transmitter.
name: American Electric Nickel 2 Candlestick Telephone

desc: American Electric "Potbelly" candlestick telephone.  Early candlestick telephones were made to be attractive.  This particular antique telephone has a small transmitter and a "Burns" long pole receiver.
name: American Electric Potbelly Candlestick Telephone

desc: Barid Equipment Co. Chicago 3 slot single lever coin collector.  When a coin is dropped in the proper slot a sound is made that is specific to that denomination.  The operator would hear the sounds and be aware of what was inserted.  It is mounted to an Antique Western Electric 2 box telephone.
name: Baird

desc: This 1C Western Electric, "Bell Atlantic" payphone came from the United Nations Building in NY. The coin chute is made by Mars. The original service log is still present.  Not the plain chrome plate in the upper left corner, Bell Atlantic started using them.   I was told when I got it that there were many booths with phones in dumpsters, this one was saved from the scrap yard. The upper housing lock is a 29A-75 and vault lock a 30C.
name: Bell Atlantic UN loc A-2

desc: Bell of Pennsylvania 1C.  This vintage payphone was made in 1976.  It is set up for 10 cent local call with dial tone first.  It is equipped with the earlier type face plate and tear drop shaped coin return lever.  The orange sign would have been added when it was converted from coin first to dial tone first.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-16 and vault  lock is a 30A.
name: Bell Of Pennsylvania 1C loc UP8

desc: Bell Atlantic, formally Bell of Pennsylvania 1C payphone.  This phone is set up for 25 cent DTF (dial tone first) operation.  Note the Bell Atlantic embossed handset, the Bell of Pennsylvania, A Bell Atlantic Co. embossed vault door and the collection box with the Bell Atlantic bar code sticker.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-16 and the vault lock is a 30C.
name: Bell Of Pennsylvania Bell Atlantic 1C loc LP8

desc: Bell South payphone.  Back around 2000 when Bell South exited the payphone business the Telephone Pioneers refurbished and sold them for $100 to the public.  I added the correct instruction cards.  The phone came with the simple Bell South door shown in the last picture.  The Olympic door on the phone was sold as an upgrade.  20A chute & Tele Service chassis.
name: Bell South

desc: Bell South 1P2 "Press Blue To Get Through".  In order to connect to their long distance service press # and 1.  Those buttons are blue and not silver like the rest.  Otherwise the phone is set up the same as a 1D  Note the nice USA Olympic embossed door, the Bell South sign in the upper left corner and the Press Blue instruction cards.  The upper housing lock is a Medico and the vault lock is a 30C
name: Bell South 1P2 Press Blue loc LP7

desc: Bell South Green touch tone payphone.  It was manufactured as a 1C and at some point was upgraded to a 1D, note it still retains the early type coin release lever.
name: Bell South Green 1971 loc C-8

desc:
(1958) In Woodbridge, N. J., a limited number of
experimental coin telephones with important
changes in appearance and internal operation have been placed on trial for a few months at various locations. The purpose of this trial, being conducted with the cooperation of the New Jersey Bell Telephone Company, is to test the operation of the new equipment.
name: Bell Telephone Laboratories Field Test

desc: British Western Electric candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone came from the UK, it has a steel body & metal shelled receiver.  It appears to be all British Western Electric. The transmitter is a BWE No. 1 made in 1923. 4001 is the BWE transmitter part number.  The phone itself is a BWE Tele No 2 (manual) revision 2 made in 1911. I think 1020 is the BWE part number.  I'm not sure what the arrow is but it may be a government/MOD mark. Thanks to Jack Ryan for decoding it.
name: British Western Electric Candlestick $350

desc: That telephone was made by the Plessey Co Ltd in 1929. It is the standard GPO style auto candlestick - the Tele No 150.  The Bakelite transmitters (Transmitter No 22) were later replacements that used the newer handset transmitter inserts.  This telephone has a dial blank in the place of a dial.
name: British, Plessey Co Dial Blank $300

desc: Green C & P Telephone, A Bell Atlantic Company.  The phone came from Virginia.  Western Electric model 1C rotary telephone set up for 25 cent initial charge.  Note the nice C & P vault door. The unusual instruction sign at the top left with the arrow pointing down to the instruction card is the kind that was used on post pay models.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-56 and the vault lock is a 30B.
name: C & P Green 1C loc C-2

desc: C&P rare 1E6 post pay payphone from Big Spring Maryland.  Note the electronics on the hopper and the post pay type sign on the upper left corner of the phone.  Also note the Bell Atlantic embossed handset.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-56 and the vault lock is a 30C.
name: C&P 1E1 loc E6

desc: Century manual candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone is nicknamed the "Split Shaft" due to the way the shaft can be split into 2 halves.  It is also what is called a "tapered shaft" due to the fact that the shaft is narrower at the top than at the bottom.  The entire body is nickel plated brass.  Note the advertising note pad attachment on the shaft.
name: Century Split Shaft Candlestick Telephone

desc: Chicago candlestick phone with Bakelite potbelly.  This antique telephone is nicknamed "Chicago Semi-potbelly".
name: Chicago Bakelite Potbelly Candlestick Telephone

desc: Chicago candlestick phone.  This model antique telephone is nicknamed "Oil Can Base" due to the shape of the phone, it looks like an old time oil can.
name: Chicago Oil Can Base 1 Candlestick Telephone

desc: Chicago candlestick phone. This model antique telephone is nicknamed "Oil Can Base" due to the shape of the phone, it looks like an old time oil can
name: Chicago Oil Can Base 2 Candlestick Telephone

desc: Couch Autophone candlestick telephone, intercom.   Similar to a dial but the operation is different, the lever is moved on the number 1-30 of the extension desired and then released to make the connection.
name: Couch Aotuphone Candlestick $300

desc: Couch Autophone.  This antique telephone is rather unique, I've seen candlestick and wall versions but none like this in my experience but I'm sure they're out there.  I was part of an automated intercom system.  Note the rotating lever type dial.
name: Couch Autophone

desc: Courtesy Pays, Courtesy Con Box Company.  Used on an honor system.  It is mounted to an antique Western Electric 50AL candlestick telephone.
name: Courtesy Coin Box Co

desc: Connecticut desk telephone.  Nicknamed the "Toaster Phone", this antique telephone is made of Gray colored thermoplastic with a metal finger wheel painted to match.  This phone was made to be part of a intercom system.
name: Ct Gray $200

desc: Connecticut desk telephone.  Nicknamed the "Toaster Phone", this antique telephone is made of metal and factory painted red, the handset is red plastic and the dial finger wheel is black painted metal.  This phone was made for the US Army Signal Corps.
name: Ct Red $250

desc: De Veau candlestick telephone/intercom.  This antique telephone does not have a signal button.
name: De Veau Straight Shaft Candl $175

desc: De Veau, tapered shaft candlestick telephone/intercom.  This is a very heavy phone with signal buttons for many different stations. .
name: De Veau Tapered Shaft 1 Candlestick Telephone

desc: De Veau, tapered shaft candlestick telephone/intercom.  This antique telephone has 10 signal buttons for different rooms in a mansion.
name: De Veau Tapered Shaft 2 Candlestick Telephone

desc: De Veau thin shaft candlestick telephone/intercom.  This appears to be a very early model with a small transmitter.  The receiver is an ost Solid.  This antique telephone has buttons marked for different rooms in a mansion.
name: De Veau Thin Shaft Candlestick Telephone

desc: Dean 'Cosmo' candlestick telephone, Dean worked for Kellogg, he went out on his own and started producing his own instruments.  This antique telephone was made to be used in rough locations such as for dispatchers.  The entire body is one piece, the mouthpiece and receiver shell are made of steel.
name: Dean 'Cosmo' Candlestick $200

desc: Dean candlestick telephone, Dean worked for Kellogg, he went out on his own and started producing his own instruments.  This antique telephone is very nice with nickel plated brass and with a fiber sleeve over the shaft.
name: Dean Candlestick $250

desc: Dean candlestick telephone/intercom.  This antique telephone is a one station of a multi-station intercom system .
name: Dean Intercom Candlestick $400

desc: Ericcson manual cradle phone.  This antique french style telephone has a candlestick base.  It is nicknamed "Grab-A-Phone".
name: Ericcson  Grab-a-phone

desc: Erricson French handset candlestick telephone.  The hook on the left is the switch hook, the one on the right is fixed, probable could have a mother-in-law receiver connected to it.
name: Ericsson French Handset Candlestick Telephone

desc: Federal candlestick telephone.  Note the very short Federal receiver on this antique telephone.
name: Federal Candlestick Telephone

desc: GPO 735 red English portable payphone.  It is similar to the ones in the red phone booths but was not intended to be mounted in place.  It came with a long cord for portability.  It operated on now obsolete 2 & 5 pence coins.  I purchased this directly from a seller in the United Kingdom.
name: GP0 735

desc: Gray Telephone Paystation Co. #10 "Shield".  the plate mounts to the back of a wall phone.  The paint and celluloid instruction card are original.  Coins dropped in the correct slots make specific sounds that are heard by the operator.  The sounds resonate from the collector through the mounting plate and into the phone where they are picked up by the transmitter.
name: GRAY 10 Shield

desc: Gray Telephone Paystation Co. #10A "Shield".  It mounts to the front of a wall phone in place of the transmitter.  The paint and celluloid instruction card are original.  Coins dropped in the correct slots make specific sounds that are heard by the operator.  The sounds resonate within the collector and they are picked up by the transmitter mounted to it.
name: GRAY 10A Shield

desc: Gray #11 coin collector.  An early model with metal instruction sign and very short tabs above the coin slots.  This would mount with a bracket to the back of a wall telephone.  Note at the top of the sign it says "quarter, dime, nickel", 25, 10, & 5 are also stenciled on the top of the case behind the slots.  Later models had taller tabs with 25, 10 & 5 on them.
name: Gray 11  1

desc: Gray #11 coin collector. A more commonly seen version with a paper instruction card in a steel frame and covered with glass. It is attached via a mounting plate to an Automatic Electric hotel type antique wall telephone.
name: Gray 11  2

desc: Gray #11 still in it's original shipping box from the Gray Manufacturing Co.  It was shipped to the Eyota Telephone Company of Eyota Minnesota.  It is the only one to my knowledge in existence to still be in it's original box.
name: Gray 11  New

desc: Gray #11A.  This antique coin collector is similar and does the same thing as a #11 but has a deeper coin drawer.  It mounts in the same manner with the same bracket to the back of a wall phone.
name: Gray 11A

desc: Gray #13A portable 5 cent coin collector with carry handle.  It is attached to a Western Electric 20B antique candlestick telephone.  When the operator asked for a deposit a nickel would be inserted which would strike & ring a bell.  The sound of the bell would resonate through the case, then through the connecting arm into the phone and would be picked up by the transmitter.  Note the nice early sing on the front.
name: Gray 13A  1

desc: NOS (new old stock), Gray #13A portable 5 cent coin collector with carry handle. It is attached to a Western Electric 20B antique candlestick telephone. When the operator asked for a deposit a nickel would be inserted which would strike & ring a bell. The sound of the bell would resonate through the case, then through the connecting arm into the phone and would be picked up by the transmitter. This coin collector was never put into service.  It also never had an instruction sign installed.
name: Gray 13A  2

desc: NOS (new old stock), Gray #13A portable 5 cent coin collector with carry handle.  When the operator asked for a deposit a nickel would be inserted which would strike & ring a bell. The sound of the bell would resonate through the case, then through a connecting arm into the phone and would be picked up by the transmitter. This coin collector was never put into service.
name: Gray 13A 3

desc: Gray #13A portable 5 cent coin collector with carry handle. When the operator asked for a deposit a nickel would be inserted which would strike & ring a bell. The sound of the bell would resonate through the case, then through a connecting arm into the phone and would be picked up by the transmitter. This coin collector was found with a virtually NOS AE 40 in Wisconsin.
name: Gray 13A 4

desc: Gray #14 portable 5, 10, 25 cent coin collector with carry handle. It is attached to a Kellogg antique candlestick telephone. When the operator asked for a deposit a coin dropped would strike & ring a bell once for a nickel, twice for a dime, a quarter would hit a gong and make a bong sound. The sound would resonate through the case, then through the connecting arm into the phone and would be picked up by the transmitter.   From the transmitter the sound is transmitted to the operator.
name: Gray 14  1

desc: Gray #14 portable 5, 10, 25 cent coin collector with carry handle. It is attached to a Western Electric 20B candlestick telephone. When the operator asked for a deposit a coin dropped would strike & ring a bell once for a nickel, twice for a dime, a quarter would hit a gong and make a bong sound. The sound would resonate through the case, then through the connecting arm into the phone and would be picked up by the transmitter. From the transmitter the sound is transmitted to the operator.
name: Gray 14 2

desc: Gray #14J handset paystation in as removed from service great condition.  It is a portable model equipped with a handset.  It was owned by an independent telephone company who equipped it with a Kellogg handset and Kellogg subset (ringer box).  In order for the operator to be able to hear the coin as they are dropped a coin signal transmitter is attached to the inside of the back cover.
name: Gray 14J

desc: Gray #150-GJ, 5 cent prepay payphone or paystation is a handset version of the Gray #150G.  These were converted & modernized by Gray from 2 piece telephones to handset models.  It is equipped with an Automatic Electric 34 handset and Western Electric dial and shroud & 10-E upper housing lock which uses a flat key.
name: Gray 150-GJ

desc: Gray 150-HJ like the 150-GJ but made to accept Canadian coins.  It was made a 5 cent prepay payphone or paystation, it looks like the coin chute was replaced to convert the phone to 10 cent operation.  It is a handset version of the Gray #150H. These were converted & modernized by Gray from 2 piece telephones to handset models. It is equipped with an Automatic Electric 34 handset and Western Electric dial and shroud.  The upper housing lock is a 29S and lower lock a 10L.
name: Gray 150-HJ

desc: Gray #150-K is a manual post-pay payphone or paystation.  All operation is controlled by the operator.  There is no collect or receive function, once a coin is dropped into the proper slot it goes directly into the coin vault.  The upper housing, lower and backboard are steel.  The upper housing lock is an E-10 which uses a flat key. This unit is mounted to a 139A bracket.
name: Gray 150-K  1

desc: Gray #150-K is a manual post-pay payphone or paystation. All operation is controlled by the operator. There is no collect or receive function, once a coin is dropped it goes directly into the coin vault.  The upper housing, lower and the backboard are steel.  The upper housing lock is a 29S.
name: Gray 150-K  2

desc: Gray #150-KJ, payphone or paystation is a handset version of the Gray #150K.  All functions are handled by the operator.  I think most if not all of these were converted or upgraded by Gray from 2 piece telephones to handset models. It is equipped with an Automatic Electric 34 handset..
name: Gray 150-KJ

desc: Gray #20 shelf or counter mount 5, 10, 25 cent coin collector. It is attached to a Western Electric 20AL antique candlestick telephone. When a coin is dropped and hits the bell or gong the sound resonates through the case, then through the connecting arm into the phone and would be picked up by the transmitter. From the transmitter the sound is transmitted to the operator.  The candlestick telephone has an unusual phone number attachment on it.
name: Gray 20

desc: Gray #21 portable paystation.  Nicknamed the "Wanamaker".  They were commonly seen in Wanamaker Department Stores.  Like the #24 but this model has a heavy cast iron body.  Nice original Bell System celluloid instruction card.  This antique telephone was recently found in Connecticut.  I really like the design of this telephone.
name: Gray 21 Wanamaker

desc: Gray #23, this paystation mounts to the front of an antique wood wall telephone in place of the transmitter assembly.  This antique paystation has a grid of holes in the backboard that are used to line up with the original transmitter mounting holes in the front of the phones case.  Basically once this is installed on the phone it converts it into a payphone.
name: Gray 23

desc: Gray #23A shelf or counter mount 5, 10, 25 cent coin collector. It is attached to a Western Electric 20B antique candlestick telephone. When the operator asked for a deposit a coin dropped would strike & ring a bell once for a nickel, twice for a dime, a quarter would hit a gong and make a bong sound. The sound would resonate through the case, then through the connecting arm into the phone and would be picked up by the transmitter. From the transmitter the sound is transmitted to the operator.
name: Gray 23A

desc: Gray #20B, very similar to the #23 but with a deeper coin drawer.  This paystation mounts to the front of an antique wood wall telephone in place of the transmitter assembly. The unit has a grid of holes in the backboard that are used to line up with the original transmitter mounting holes in the front of the phones case. Basically once this is installed on the phone it converts it into a payphone.
name: Gray 23B

desc: The Gray 23C is very similar to the 23D.  The main difference is that the vault is shallower and holds less coins.  While the 23D was used mostly in public places the 23C was used in areas with less traffic such as hotel rooms.  This particular example is not exactly stock, it looks like it went through some transformations over the years.
name: Gray 23C

desc: Gray #23D, a complete 2 piece paystation.  Like an antique telephone desk stand it connects to a subset (ringer box).  The operation is completely under the control of the operator.
name: Gray 23D

desc: The earliest version of the 23D. The distinction of early is: thin backboard, Gray transmitter mount, all cast iron (including bottom) with two terminals.  The bonus is the coin reject with intact coin reject basket.  Not many survived and the internal basket is indeed very rare.  Most of the coin reject type 23 D's have the side slot.  Equipped with a WE OST receiver and original WE celluloid instruction card.  Pictures with the coin chute removed expose the return chute & transmitter wiring.
name: Gray 23D First Version

desc: Gray #23J, a complete handset paystation. Like an antique cradle telephone it connects to a subset (ringer box). The operation is completely under the control of the operator.  Note this aluminum model has one not 3 separate ones.
name: Gray 23J

desc: Gray #23J, a complete handset paystation. Like an antique cradle telephone it connects to a subset (ringer box). The operation is completely under the control of the operator.  Customers would use this phone to contact a Western Union operator in order to send a telegram.  The operator would ask for payment and listen to the coins being dropped.  Since it is a handset telephone a signal transmitter is mounted to the back plate.
name: Gray 23J  WU

desc: Gray #24 portable paystation.  Nicknamed the "Wanamaker".  They were commonly seen in Wanamaker Department Stores.  Like the #21 but this model has an aluminum body.  I really like the design of this telephone.
name: Gray 24 Wanamaker

desc: Gray #34-A-10, 5 cent Semi-post-pay paystation or payphone.  Semi-post-pay is an automated system, the user lifts the receiver and dials the number desired, once the party answers the user drops a coin in.  This phone has a very unusual coin return assembly with a very thin chute.  This type chute probably clogged often.
name: Gray 34-A-10

desc: Gray #34-A-11 semi-post-pay paystation or payphone.  It works on an automated system.  The caller lifts the handset and dials the desired number.  When the party answers a coin is deposited.  Equipped with an AE 34 type handset, AE dial with pot metal shroud and mounted to a 139A bracket.
name: Gray 34-A-11

desc: Gray #34-A-11, 5 cent semi-post-pay paystation or payphone.  I restored this phone several years ago, it is equipped with an AE 34 type handset, AE dial with pot metal shroud and is mounted to an early type 139A bracket.  This phone made for the Strowger Telephone System has the rare thin coin return chute.
name: Gray 34-A-11 Bronze

desc: Gray #34-A-9, 5 cent, automatic, prepay paystation or payphone with an AE type 34 handset, AE dial with pot metal shroud.  Take a look at the nice Gray embossed hopper.
name: Gray 34-A-9

desc: Gray #50G, this seems to be the model everyone looks for, the 50G is a 5 cent automatic payphone or paystation.  This one is of a late production run, it has a steel upper and backboard vs. the earlier cast iron ones.  While this antique payphone wasn't made for the "Bell System" it does have components made by Western Electric including the dial & shroud, the transmitter and the receiver.
name: Gray 50-G

desc: Gray #50K  manual payphone or paystation. This one is of a late production run, it has a steel upper and backboard vs. the earlier cast iron ones. While this antique payphone wasn't made for the "Bell System" it does have components made by Western Electric including the transmitter and the receiver.  All functions were handled by the operator.
name: Gray 50-K

desc: Gray #62 5 cent prepay payphone or paystation.  Probably made towards the end of Gray's existence, when Automatic Electric took over they started making model 62s.  This phone is equipped with Automatic Electric components including the dial,the receiver and the transmitter.  This same model was also produced with a handset.
name: Gray 62 2 piece

desc: Gray #62, 5 cent prepay payphone or paystation. Probably made towards the end of Gray's existence, when Automatic Electric took over they started making model 62s. This phone is equipped with an Automatic Electric type 34 handset.  The dial is AE, the shroud is Bakelite with a nice porcelain "daisy" face.  It looks like at some point it was converted/upgraded to 10 cent operation.  It is attached to a 139A bracket.
name: Gray 62 Handset

desc: Gray #7 very early antique coin collector ca 1890s.  The transmitter arm is similar to the #5 type.  This mounts to the front of a wood phone in place of the transmitter assembly.  My #7 is attached to an early Western Electric type 85 common battery telephone.
name: Gray 7  1

desc: Gray #7, these coin collectors mount to the front of a wall phone in place of the transmitter assembly, a transmitter is then attached to the #7 creating a complete payphone.
name: Gray 7  2

desc: Gray #75-A, 5 cent prepay payphone or paystation made for the Automatic Electric Co.  The phone has what is called a shoe on the front.  The shoe is the part that the transmitter and dial mount to.  The cast iron upper housing has no dial cup cut into it.  It is equipped with an early flat vault door with a tag on it with the key number engraved.
name: Gray 75-A

desc: Gray #7A, collector mounts to the front of a wall phone in the same manner as a #7.  The only difference is the #7A has a larger coin drawer, it can hold more coins.  My #7A is mounted to an antique Western Electric type 317 telephone.
name: Gray 7A

desc: Gray #8A, 5 cent coin collector.  This is a rather rare model, it mounts via the mounting plate to the back of a wall telephone.  It has an early metal directions sign.  When the operator was called to make a call she would have the caller drop a nickel in the single slot.  The coin would fall hitting a bell, the sound would resonate from the collector through bracket and to the phone where it would be picked up by the transmitter so that the operator could hear it.
name: Gray 8A

desc: GRAY #AE-750, 5 cent post-pay payphone or paystation, bronze in color, I restored this phone several years ago.  It was made for the Automatic Electric Co.  It has the unusual thin coin return chute seen on a few of my other antique payphones. It has the "shoe" on the front that mounts the dial and transmitter.  The housing is mad of steel.
name: Gray AE-750  1

desc: GRAY #AE-750, 5 cent simi-post-pay payphone or paystation, bronze in color, I restored this phone several years ago. It was made for the Automatic Electric Co. It has the unusual thin coin return chute seen on a few of my other antique payphones. It has the "shoe" on the front that mounts the "Mercedes" dial and transmitter. The housing is mad of steel.  This is an early example, it has no dial cup cut into the upper housing and a flat steel vault door.
name: Gray AE-750  2

desc: Gray #150G, this one was made for the Bell System, it has a Western Electric coin relay.  The 150G is a 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation, it is wired for anti-side-tone. The upper and backboard are cast iron.  The dial, receiver & transmitter are all Western Electric.
name: Gray WE 150-G

desc: Gray #150K manual Post-pay payphone or paystation. This one was made for the Bell System. The upper and backboard are cast iron.  The receiver and transmitter are Western Electric.  All functions were handled by the operator.
name: Gray WE 150-K

desc: Gray #150K manual Post-pay payphone or paystation. This one was made for the Bell System. The upper and backboard are cast iron. The receiver and transmitter are Western Electric. All functions were handled by the operator.  Note the early "bow tie" transmitter mount.  Also note the early Gray vault door with the slightly (to the left) offset keyhole.
name: Gray WE 150-K 2

desc: Gray/Western Electric 174C.  This payphone originally was a 2 piece unit such as a 50G (see plate that covers the transmitter mounting holes on the front).  It was converted by Western Electric from 5 cents to a 10 cent phone with a handset.  The phone was designated 174C a manual coin first anti sidetone model, that why the suffix is C not G.  "G" would have been if it was made with a dial.  At some point the dial was added while the phone was in the field.  Note the phone is attached to a 139A cast iron counter mount base.  The upper housing lock is a 10G and vault lock is a 12B.
name: Gray WE 174C

desc: Gray #50A, manual prepay payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it has a Western Electric coin relay.  This is the first model of the standard 3 slot payphone ca 1911.  The upper, backboard and lower are cast iron.  The name tag above the vault is bronze.  The vault door is flat steel.  There is no dial cup cut into the upper housing, this was made before the dial was available.  Production was short lived because the cast vault was extremely vulnerable.  The lower lock is an 11A and the upper housing lock is an E10E.
name: Gray WE 50-A  1

desc: Gray #50A, 5 cent manual prepay payphone or paystation.  This is the second and rarest version of the 50A paystation ca 1916.  the upper and backboard are cast iron, the lower is steel but it is different from the type used on the later models such as the 50G.  There is no dial cup cut in the upper housing because it was made before the dial was available.  The coin relay in this phone is the oldest and only one know to exist.  Very early self locking 1A coin box.   The lower lock is an 11A and the upper housing lock is an E10E.
name: Gray WE 50-A  2

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, dial, receiver & transmitter.  The upper and backboard are cast iron.  Note the early vault door with the keyhole positioned further left of center than most others, the opening is of a different shape as well.  The paystation is mounted to an early type 139A bracket.
name: Gray WE 50-G  1 (early)

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, dial, receiver & transmitter.  The upper and backboard are cast iron.  Note the early vault door with the keyhole positioned further left of center than most others, the opening is of a different shape as well.  Also not the 1B instruction card holder.
name: Gray WE 50-G  2 (Early Door)

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, dial, receiver & transmitter.  The upper and backboard are cast iron.   FOR SALE!!  $2500.00
name: Gray WE 50-G  3

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, dial, receiver & transmitter.  The upper and backboard are cast iron.   SOLD!!
name: Gray WE 50-G  4  SOLD

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, dial, receiver & transmitter.  There is an anti-stuffing device installed.  If the coin return chute is stuffed it jams up the coin relay preventing any coins being returned.  The upper and backboard are cast iron.  Note the 1B instruction card holder.
name: Gray WE 50-G  5 (Anti Stuffing)

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent manual prepay  payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, receiver & transmitter.  The upper and backboard are cast iron.  The user of this paystation would deposit a nickel to reach an operator.
name: Gray WE 50-G  6 Non-dial  1

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, dial, receiver & transmitter.  The upper and lower are steel the backboard is cast iron.  Note the seal still on the coin box.  This paystation is in beautiful original condition.
name: Gray WE 50-G  7 (Late)

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent manual prepay payphone or paystation. This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, receiver & transmitter. The upper and backboard are cast iron. The user of this paystation would deposit a nickel to reach an operator.  Note the early 1A coin receptacle and the out of service sign.  The number of the phone was shown in a window slot in the instruction card.
name: Gray WE 50-G 6 Non-dial 2

desc: Gray #50G, 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation. This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, dial, receiver & transmitter.  The lead coin chute is Western Electric as well.  The upper and the backboard are cast iron. Note the great instruction card with the phone number on it.
name: Gray WE 50-G 8

desc: Gray #50H, 5 cent prepay automatic payphone or paystation from Detroit. This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric coin relay, dial, 706 receiver & 635 "bulldog" transmitter. Otherwise like the 50G the 50H was made to also take Canadian coins.  The coin chute was upgraded in the 50s (partial 10 cent conversion).  The upper and backboard are cast iron. Note the 1B instruction card holder.  Also note the coin deflector attachment behind the dial.
name: Gray WE 50-H

desc: Gray #50K, manual post-pay payphone or paystation.  This antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric receiver & transmitter with brass mouthpiece.  The upper and backboard are cast iron.  Note the early flat steel vault door.
name: Gray WE 50-K

desc: Gray #50K, manual post-pay payphone or paystation. This 1929 antique telephone was made for the Bell System, it is equipped with Western Electric receiver & transmitter. The upper and backboard are cast iron. Note the early plywood backboard and 315H subset.  The vault contains an open top 2A coin receptacle.  The upper housing lock is a 10G and Vault lock is a 12B.  This is probably the most like new 1920s paystation out there!
name: Gray WE 50-K 2

desc: Gray/Western Electric #D-96719, probably started out as a 150G but was specially modified by Western Electric.  It is a 5 cent automatic prepay payphone or paystation. D part numbers usually refer to modifications.  This antique telephone has had a relay added with a set of dial shorting contacts.  It is all other ways is like a 150G.  The upper and backboard are cast iron.
name: Gray WE D-96719

desc: Gray 50L like the 50K with a special coin chute to accept Canadian coins.  This is a manual post-pay payphone or paystation. This antique telephone was made for the Bell System of Canada, it is equipped with a Northern Electric receiver & Western Electric transmitter with reinforced mouthpiece. The upper and backboard are cast iron.  The upper housing lock is a 10E with a flat keyway and the vault lock is a 12B.
name: Gray Western Electric 50-L

desc: Green Western Electric very early model 1A payphone made in 1968.  Note the relay at the top left of the chassis and the coin signal transmitter at the top right of the coin chute.  Due to coin signal scams this transmitter allowed the operator to actually hear the coin in the chute.  The totalizer has no provision for DTF (dial tone first). Also, note the short coin box that sits on a spacer and the metal Bell System seal.  The upper lock is a 29A-24 and the lower is a 30A.
name: Green 1968 1A NY Tel Co Westchester loc C-1

desc: Holtzer  Ccabot, Ness,  multi-station intercom.  This antique telephone is equipped with a Solid ost receiver.
name: Holtzer Cabot, Ness

desc: Hotel telephone collector!  Drop a nickel in a nickel, turn the knob back and forth and you receive a set number of hours of telephone service.  Seems like a bargain to me!
name: Hotel Collector

desc: Illinois Bell 1D payphone. This Bell System dial tone first 25 cent payphone came from Chicago. The housing was made by AT&T.  Note the Ameritech sticker on the coin box.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-22 and the vault lock is a 30C.
name: Illinois Bell

desc: Illinois Bell, Ameritech green 1C payphone set up for 50 cent dial tone first service.  Green payphones were more prevalent in Illinois than black ones.  Note the nice Illinois Bell an Ameritech Co. embossed vault door and the Ameritech bar code sticker on the coin box.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-22 and the vault lock is a 30C.
name: Illinois Bell Ameritech 1C loc LP5

desc: Illinois Bell an Americech Co. payphone from the Chicago area.  It still sports it's original green finish.  Made by Western Electric as a 1A.  It was upgraded over the years with a 1D type chassis and a Lucent coin chute.  Western Electric became Lucent after the breakup.  Original gray handset.  29A-22 upper lock, 30C vault lock.
name: Illinois Bell Grean Chicago loc B-1

desc: Kellogg coin collector, manufactured by Baird.  The collector has slots for nickel, dime & quarter.  When a coin is dropped into the correct slot and then the arm is pulled a sound is made unique to the inserted denomination.  The sound would resonate from the collector, through the bracket to the telephone and then be picked up by the transmitter for the operator to hear.  My collector is mounted to an antique Chicago 2 box telephone.
name: Kellogg

desc: Kellogg candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone was made for the Postal Telegraph Co.  The housing is painted brown, the mouthpiece and the receiver are brown as well.
name: Kellogg  Postal Telegraph Co. Candlestick Telephone

desc: Kellogg candlestick telephone ca 1901.  This is a very early version of a Kellogg stick.  This antique telephone has a very wide weighted base.  The receiver is an early version not seen on later phones.  The transmitter faceplate has a beveled edge and is nicely embossed.  The transmitter cup is held on by a bolt and thumbscrew.  The is a little pin at the top of the perch to stop the transmitter from tilting back to far.
name: Kellogg 1901 Candlestick Telephone

desc: Kellogg 700 series, this antique telephone is nicknamed "Ash Tray".  It is all Bakelite and would be used with a subset as part of a manual telephone system.
name: Kellogg 700 Ash Tray

desc: Kellogg 725 Masterphone, this antique telephone is metal with a Bakelite handset. It would be used with a subset as part of a manual telephone system, it has a dial blank so it could be converted to automatic.
name: Kellogg 725 Master Phone

desc: Kellogg 900 series, this antique telephone is nicknamed "Pyramid".  It is all Bakelite and would be used with a subset as part of a manual telephone system..  This is the most Deco inspired telephone I know of.
name: Kellogg 900 Pyramid

desc: Kellogg 925 series, this antique telephone is nicknamed "Ash Tray".  It is all Bakelite and would be used with a subset as part of a manual telephone system.  The phone is equipped with a dial blank, it could at any time have a dial added and be converted to automatic.  Very sleek looking phone.
name: Kellogg 925 Ash Tray

desc: Kellogg candlestick telephone with dial.  Note the Deco design on the phone number card.
name: Kellogg Dial Candlestick $300

desc: Kellogg F-115 manual cradle-phone.  This antique telephone has a French inspired appearance.  It has a candlestick phone base.  It is nicknamed "Grab-A-Phone".
name: Kellogg F-115 Grab A Phone

desc: Kellogg candlestick telephone made for the Frontier Telephone Company.  This antique telephone has a nice nickel plate finish, The cup is held on by a bolt and thumb screw.  Note the F for Frontier in the hook.
name: Kellogg Frontier Tel Co. Candlestick Telephone

desc: Kellogg automatic desk phone, this antique telephone is made of brown Bakelite.  It was used as part of a Kellogg "Select-O-Phone private exchange.  The same body was used for standard phones as well, they were made of both metal (painted black) or black Bakelite.
name: Kellogg Red Bar Brown $250

desc: Kellogg Select O Phone, brown painted metal housing with brown Bakelite handset.  The dial finger wheel is chrome. This would have been used in a private exchange.  This antique telephone is "new old stock" (NOS), it was used as a salesman's display and was never put into service.
name: Kellogg Select O Phone Brown

desc: Blue Ericofon, I collect the original Ericofons that were made in Sweden by Ericsson.  They were used as desk phones, small and compact so as to not take up too much space.  The dial is on the bottom, the red button in the center of the dial was actuated then the phone was put down to hang it up.  This model was later made by North Electric and others.
name: L M Ericcson Blue

desc: Gray Ericofon, I collect the original Ericofons that were made in Sweden by Ericsson.  They were used as desk phones, small and compact so as to not take up too much space.  The dial is on the bottom, the red button in the center of the dial was actuated then the phone was put down to hang it up.  This model was later made by North Electric and others.
name: L M Ericcson Gray

The dial is on the bottom, the red button in the center of the dial was actuated then the phone was put down to hang it up.  This model was later made by North Electric and others.
name: L M Ericcson Green

The dial is on the bottom, the red button in the center of the dial was actuated then the phone was put down to hang it up.  This model was later made by North Electric and others.
name: L M Ericcson Ivory

The dial is on the bottom, the red button in the center of the dial was actuated then the phone was put down to hang it up.  This model was later made by North Electric and others.
name: L M Ericcson Red

desc: Yellow Ericofon, I collect the original Ericofons that were made in Sweden by Ericsson.  They were used as desk phones, small and compact so as to not take up too much space.  The dial is on the bottom, the red button in the center of the dial was actuated then the phone was put down to hang it up.  This model was later made by North Electric and others.
name: L M Ericcson Yellow

desc: Leich automatic desk phone.  This antique telephone has a nice chrome plated cradle and dial.  The rest of the phone including the handset are Bakelite.  There is a lower section that contains the bell.  These phones were also sold without that section that were for use with a subset.
name: Leich

desc: Leich, manual candlestick telephone.
name: Leich 1 Candlestick $200

desc: Leich candlestick telephone, black painted and nickel plated parts.
name: Leich 2 Candlestick $200

desc: Loeffler candlestick telephone/intercom.  Loeffler came here from Germany around 1900 and started his company that still exists today.  They specialize in "Doorman Phones".  This antique telephone would have been part of a mansion intercom system.
name: Loeffler 5 Button Intercom Candlestick $200

desc: Loeffler candlestick telephone/intercom. Loeffler came here from Germany around 1900 and started his company that still exists today. They specialize in "Doorman Phones". This antique telephone would have been part of a mansion intercom system.
name: Loeffler 8 Button Intercom Candlestick Telephone

desc: Loeffler cradle-phone/intercom. Loeffler came here from Germany around 1900 and started his company that still exists today. They specialize in "Doorman Phones". This antique telephone would have been part of an intercom system.  It has 3 call buttons on the base.
name: Loeffler Cradle

desc: Manhattan manual candlestick telephone.  This beautiful antique telephone is nicknamed a "Rope Shaft".  It has outside terminal, outside contacts and is equipped with a metal housed Manhattan "watch case" receiver.
name: Manhattan Rope Shaft Candlestick Telephone

desc: Compact Antique Manhattan Wall Telephone ca 1900 equipped with a Manhattan long pole receiver.  Note the Steer type receiver hook.
name: Manhattan Wall Telephone

desc: Monarch manual candlestick telephone.
name: Monarch Candlestick $225

desc: Western Electric model 1E single slot payphone made in 1973.  It operation is similar to the old 193G, 212G and many other post pay 3 slot payphones.  The caller would lift the handset, listen for dial tone and dial the desired number.  After hearing a second dial tone a deposit in this case of 20 cents for a local call would be made.  This phone came from Pie Town New Mexico.  It has beautiful original green paint and the original gray handset with the seldom seen black grommet.  Note the instruction plate in the upper left corner that was used on the 1E models.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-63 and the vault lock is a 30A.
name: Mountain Bell 1E Green loc LP2

desc: Mountain Bell from New Mexico.  This vintage 1C payphone is set up for 20 cent coin first service.  The housing as well as the vault door are green and the handset is gray.  Note the white porcelain instruction sign on the upper left corner.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-63 and the vault lock is a 30A.
name: Mountain Bell, New Mexico 1C loc LP1

desc: Northern Electric #1236Q3, early 10 key touch tone prepay payphone.  10 button phones and payphones were made around 1964 or 1965, they are rare collectables.  This is a complete payphone, all the components are within the case, no subset is needed.
name: NE 1236

desc: Northern Electric 202 automatic cradle-phone.  This antique telephone is very similar to the Western Electric version.  It is equipped with a Northern Electric E handset and Northern Electric number 4 dial
name: NE 202

desc: Northern Electric 20B manual candlestick telephone.  This antique telephone is all nickel plated brass.  It is a Northern Electric (Canada) version of the type made by Western Electric.  Note the bolt and thumbscrew attaching the transmitter to the perch.
name: NE 20B Candlestick Telephone

desc: Northern Electric #2236QC, 12 Key touch tone prepay payphone.  This is a complete unit, everything is enclosed within the case.  No subset needed.  Note the seal still on the coin box.  I believe this phone originated at the Rochester (NY) Telephone Company.
name: NE 2236QC

desc: Northern Electric N203D, manual post-pay payphone or paystation.   All functions would have been controlled by the operator.
name: NE N203D

desc: Northern Electric N50AL, automatic dial candlestick phone. This antique telephone is similar to the Western Electric version but not exact. The base is a different shape with a terminal strip on the inside.  The receiver and transmitter are Northern Electric. The dial is a Western Electric 2AB.  The phone appears to have been refurbished in the 1930s.
name: NE N50AL Candlestick Telephone

desc: Northern Electric "Uniphone".  This antique telephone is made of brown Bakelite.  Made by Northern Electric, Canada.  It is like a wide version of the more common 302 telephone.
name: NE Uniphone Brown $300

desc: Northern Electric Uniphone,  Bakelite housing with 5 sided handset.  Equipped with NE number 5 dial.
name: NE Unipnone SOLD

desc: New Jersey Bell Telephone Co. green 1A payphone.  The 1A is a coin first model and is not convertible to dial tone first.  Note the metal coin return chute (with the red X on it) on the coin scanner.  Also note the early dull chrome face plate and coin return assembly.  The phone also has the early tear drop shaped coin return lever and early gray plastic tongue in the handset cradle.  The handset is without a rubber grommet.  Interesting, the instruction card tells you what exchanges you can dial from the phone.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-46 and the vault lock is a 30A.
name: NJ Bell 1A loc E1

desc: New Jersey Bell 1979 1C payphone.  This vintage phone is set up for 10 cent DTF (dial tone first) service.  The phone is in great condition and came out of service with a coiled handset cord, which I replaced because it was dried out.  The cord is thicker than a standard wall phone cord.  A cord of this type would have been used on a phone located in a business where the workers grabbed the phone while working or similar situation.  The upper housing lock is a 29A-46 and the vault lock is a 30A.
name: NJ Bell 1C Coiled Cord loc LP4

desc: Western Electric 1978 model 1C payphone.  It is set up for 10 cent, dial tone first.  the number card has a Haledon (pronounced "hail-done") NJ phone number with the original "201" area code instead of the current "973".  I guess it was installed at a time of change, it is stamped in several places in red "DTF" (Dial Tone First).  The upper housing lock is a 29A-46 and the lower is a 30B.
name: NJ Bell Haledon 1C loc A-3

desc: Western Electric 1D payphone. This Bell System dial tone first 20 cent payphone came from Port Libern, Jersey City NJ. Note the gray colored handset and the embossed vault door.  Also note the Bell Atlantic bar code sticker on the coin box and all the papers found within the phone. The upper housing lock is a 29A-46 and the lower is 30C
name: NJ Tel Port Libern, Jersey City A-6

desc: NOS (new old stock) Western Electric early model 1A payphone made in 1970. Note the relay at the top left of the chassis. The totalizer has no provision for DTF (dial tone first). Also, note the NOS black coin box with a metal seal marked NYT (New York Telephone) and MW (Manhattan West).  Note the shrink wrapped backboard for the installer.  The upper lock is a 29A-77 (which is one of 2 different upper locks used in Manhattan the other was the 29A-75) The lock that secures the vault door is a 30A..
name: NOS 1970 1A NY Tel Co loc C-4

desc: NOS (new old stock) 1976 Western Electric 1C pre-pay payphone.  It has the early white porcelain instruction sign at the upper left corner and the original gray colored handset.
